SIMPLE: rigor
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rigor
<hw>Ri"gor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. See
<er>Rigor</er>., below.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Rigidity;
stiffness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(ed.)</fld> <def>A sense of chilliness, with
contraction of the skin; a convulsive shuddering or tremor, as in the
chill preceding a fever.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs>\'d8<col><b>Rigor caloris</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr> <ety>[L.,
rigor of heat]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>a form of rigor mortis
induced by heat, as when the muscle of a mammal is heated to about
50⟦deg⟧ C.</cd> -- \'d8<col><b>Rigor mortis</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr>
<ety>[L. , rigor of death]</ety>, <cd>death stiffening; the rigidity of
the muscles that occurs at death and lasts till decomposition sets in.
It is due to the formation of myosin by the coagulation of the contents
of the individual muscle fibers.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rigor</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rigor
<hw>Rig"or</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>rigour</ets>,
OF. <ets>rigour</ets>, F. <ets>rigueur</ets>, from L. <ets>rigor</ets>,
fr. <ets>rigere</ets> to be stiff. See <er>Rigid</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>rigour</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
becoming stiff or rigid; the state of being rigid; rigidity; stiffness;
hardness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rest his look⟦br⟧
Bound with Gorgonian <qex>rigor</qex> not to move.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>See 1st <er>Rigor</er>,
2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Severity of climate or season; inclemency; <as>as,
the <ex>rigor</ex> of the storm; the <ex>rigors</ex> of
winter.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Stiffness of opinion or temper; rugged sternness;
hardness; relentless severity; hard-heartedness; cruelty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All his <qex>rigor</qex> is turned to grief and pity.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I shall be condemn'd⟦br⟧
Upon surmises, . . . I tell you⟦br⟧
'T is <qex>rigor</qex> and not law.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Exactness without allowance, deviation, or
indulgence; strictness; <as>as, the <ex>rigor</ex> of criticism; to
execute a law with <ex>rigor</ex>; to enforce moral duties with
<ex>rigor</ex></as>; -- opposed to <ant>lenity</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Severity of life; austerity; voluntary submission to
pain, abstinence, or mortification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The prince lived in this convent with all the <qex>rigor</qex> and
austerity of a capuchin.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Violence; force; fury.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose raging <qex>rigor</qex> neither steel nor brass could
stay.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Stiffness; rigidness; inflexibility; severity;
austerity; sternness; harshness; strictness; exactness.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rigorism</ent>⟦br⟧
